{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}} The '''Munich Biennale''' ({{lang-de|'''Münchener Biennale'''}}) is an [[opera festival]] in the city of [[Munich]]. The full German name is ''Internationales Festival für neues Musiktheater'', literally: International Festival for New Music Theater. The biennial festival was created in 1988 by [[Hans Werner Henze]] and is held in even-numbered years over 2&ndash;3 weeks in the late spring. The festival concentrates on world premieres of theater-related [[contemporary music]], with a particular focus on commissioning first operas from young composers.<ref>[http://www.evs-musikstiftung.ch/en/grants-in-aid/grants-in-aid-archive/2010/festivals/ Munich Biennale Concert Series: Biennale plus] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120730192251/http://www.evs-musikstiftung.ch/en/grants-in-aid/grants-in-aid-archive/2010/festivals/ |date=30 July 2012 }} Ernst von Siemens music foundation 2010</ref><ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/books?ei=Ip-PTYrTKc34sgbW4sSHCg&ct=result&id=Ze8YAQAAIAAJ&dq=Munich+Biennale++Hans+Werner+Henze&q=Hans+Werner+Henze+1988+#search_anchor | title =Hans Werner Henze: Komponist der Gegenwart | page = 117}}</ref>
==The first four festivals, under Henze== Henze, himself a prolific composer of operas, described the genesis of the festival like this: {{quote|The whole story started with a query from the departmental head of the (Munich) cultural office ... whether I ... would be interested in considering creating some sort of civic music festival in Munich. After a period of time I suggested organizing something that had been lacking up until that point, something that also did not exist anywhere else in the world and yet was an urgent necessity &ndash; namely, a place where the young generation of composers interested in theatre ... could realize their ideas.<ref name="centre-The whole">{{cite web |url = http://www.muenchenerbiennale.de/standard/en/the_festival festival history pages |title = Munich Biennale Official website |accessdate = 27 March 2011 |last = |first = |date = |publisher = Munich Biennale }}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>}}
Henze curated the first four festivals, from 1988 to 1994, and established the general format of most of the festivals that followed.<ref>Official website, [http://www.muenchenerbiennale.de/standard/en/archive/1988/ archive notes to first biennale, 1988] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120905001606/http://www.muenchenerbiennale.de/standard/en/archive/1988/ |date=5 September 2012 }}</ref> Short runs of the premiered operas are preceded by talks and additional concerts from the featured composers, to introduce the audiences to their ideas and music.<ref>Official website, [http://www.muenchener-biennale.de/klangspuren/index.php?lang=en&id=_06 Klangspuren (discussion concerts) archive] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110401095459/http://www.muenchener-biennale.de/klangspuren/index.php?lang=en |date=1 April 2011 }}</ref>
==The later festivals, under Peter Ruzicka== [[Peter Ruzicka]] took over as artistic director ("one of the most influential administrative/ artistic positions in the European music-theatre scene")<ref>Salzman, Desi, p.&nbsp;164</ref> in 1996, with that year's biennale being jointly curated by Henze. Ruzicka broadened the scope of the works presented, with more emphasis on works using multimedia, and moving away from the text-based sources that characterised the period curated by Henze.<ref>Official website, [http://www.muenchenerbiennale.de/standard/en/archive/1996/ archive notes to fifth biennale, 1996]{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
